<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<chapter xml:id="chapter-3" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Fundamental Forces</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
        Consider an air parcel in the shape of a rectangular prism centered at <m>(x_0, y_0, z_0)</m>
        with edges parallel to the <m>x</m>-, <m>y</m>-, and <m>z</m>-axes of the local Cartesian coordinate system
        and length, width, and height <m>\delta x</m>, <m>\delta y</m>, and <m>\delta z</m>, respectively,
        where <m>\delta</m> indicates each dimension is immeasurably small (<xref ref="ch3-air-parcel" text="type-global" />).
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="ch3-air-parcel">
        <caption>
            An air parcel centered at <m>(x_0,y_0,z_0)</m>
            with edges parallel to the <m>x</m>-, <m>y</m>-, and <m>z</m>-axes of the local Cartesian coordinate system
            and length <m>\delta x</m> [m], width <m>\delta y</m> [m], and height <m>\delta z</m> [m].
        </caption>
        <image source="images/ch1-volume-element.png" width="60%">
            <shortdescription>
                Rectangular prism with center point and length, width, and height.
            </shortdescription>
        </image>
    </figure>

  <p>
    Recall from <xref ref="chapter-1" /> that we can regard this air parcel as having uniform density
    <m>\rho</m> [<m>\text{kg} \, \text{m}^{-3}</m>].
    Thus, its mass also is distributed uniformly throughout its volume and is given by <m>m = \rho \, \delta x \, \delta y \, \delta z</m> [kg].
  </p>

  <p>
    Let's explore the forces acting on this air parcel and how they affect its motion.
  </p>

  <note>
    <title>Handling mass</title>

    <p>
        Since it is not reasonable to measure the mass of air parcels in real life,
        we will employ force <em>per unit mass</em>,
        which is equivalent to acceleration and could be called <em>specific</em> force.
    </p>
    
  </note>

  </introduction>

  <xi:include href="ch3-section-gravitational-force.ptx" />
